# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cranks-restaurant
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cranks-restaurant/1890-by-gordon-ramsay] The restaurant was established in 2022 by Gordon Ramsay in partnership with the Savoy Hotel in which it is located.
[src:cranks-restaurant/1890-by-gordon-ramsay] The restaurant was named in honour of chef Auguste Escoffier who began working at the hotel in 1890.
[src:cranks-restaurant/1890-by-gordon-ramsay] It was first awarded a Michelin star in 2024.
[src:cranks-restaurant/64-goodge-street] The restaurant was established in 2023 by Woodhead Restaurant Group as a sister restaurant to Portland and Clipstone in a former travel agent.
[src:cranks-restaurant/64-goodge-street] Shortly after, it received positive reviews by Giles Coren and Grace Dent in *The Times* and *The Guardian* respectively.
[src:cranks-restaurant/64-goodge-street] It was first awarded a Michelin-Star in 2025.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] In 2012, Andrew Wong, a third-generation restaurateur, opened A.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] Wong, named after his parents, in Pimlico and became its chef patron.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] The site was previously the location of his parents' Cantonese restaurant Kym.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] Wong's wife Nathalie manages the restaurant.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] Among notable guests of the restaurant were brothers Ferran and Albert Adrià of El Bulli.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] The restaurant has provided traditional Cantonese dishes with modern British twists.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] The menu has been seasonal and included Peking duck, *guotie* (pan-fried dumpling) and *xiaolongbao* (Shanghai pork dumpling) with ginger-flavoured vinegar foam.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] It has also offered the "Taste of China" tasting menu, which included "soy chicken, ginger oil osetra caviar wrap", Shaanxi shredded lamb 'burger' "with Xinjiang pomegranate salad", *char siu* "with grated foie gras", "Chengdu street tofu", "Anhui fermented seabass", and "Wuwei smoked duck" (无为熏鸭).
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] Wong also offered a Xinjiang-inspired dish of deep-fried beef strips with chili and a sauce; "'1,000 chili' chicken with snails and Sichuan pepper"; Kung Pao chicken; "seared wagyu beef with mint, chili and lemongrass"; aubergine with Sichuan sauce; and crispy noodles with brown gravy.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] It also has offered dim sum dishes, like prawn cracker with deep-fried seaweed and "pork and prawn dumpling" with "a citrus foam", and desserts, like duck egg custard and "poached merengue with fruit textures".
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] Wong also offered "Why We Don't Eat Shark Fin Soup", a soup dish containing agar and chicken broth with oil extracted from steamed ham "rolled in sugar".
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] Derived from shark fin soup, Wong's dish substituted agar for shark fins because shark finning is banned in the United Kingdom and elsewhere.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] Wong also offered "Why The Buddha Didn't Jump Over the Wall" ("barbecued sweet potato with some fermented, salted black-bean relish"), inspired by the Columbian exchange in the 1500s and based on a popular Cantonese dish of "pumpkin and black bean sauce".
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] Wong earned its first Michelin star in October 2017.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] In January 2021, it became the first Chinese restaurant outside Asia to achieve two Michelin stars.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] Ben McCormack in November 2018 called A.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] Wong "the best restaurant in Victoria" and "possibly the best Chinese restaurant in Europe".
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] Wong was born in early 1980s into a family that operates Chinese restaurants, including his parents Albert and Annie.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] Wong's grandfather, a Chinese immigrant, owned some East End pubs and a restaurant in Chinatown, London.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] Wong initially did not aspire a career in hospitality, and his father wanted him to pursue further education.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] Wong attended the University of Oxford for a bachelor's degree in chemistry but did not finish after one year and a half.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] He then studied social anthropology at the London School of Economics.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] In 2003, due to his father's death, Wong decided to help his mother Annie run the family's four remaining Chinese restaurants, including one Cantonese restaurant, Kym's, opened in 1985 by Wong's parents and named after his grandmother.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] Wong then took cooking classes at Westminster Kingsway College and spent six months in China studying varieties of Chinese cuisine.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] Wong opened another Chinese restaurant Baoshuan in New Delhi in 2018.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] He also operated another Chinese restaurant Kym's, which lasted from March 2019 to late 2020, in Bloomberg Arcade of London.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] He became a research associate at the SOAS Food Studies Centre of the SOAS University of London in May 2020.
[src:cranks-restaurant/a-wong] Wong also co-hosts *XO Soused*, a podcast exploring the cultural history of Chinese food, with Dr Mukta Das, food anthropologist at the SOAS Food Studies Centre.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] The first Cranks opened at 22 Carnaby Street, London, in 1961.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] In 1968 there were 16 vegetarian restaurants in London and 18 in the United Kingdom.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] Although it was by no means the first vegetarian restaurant in the U.K. – Sir George Newnes, 1st Baronet opened a successful vegetarian restaurant in Manchester in 1881 called Vegetarian Company's Saloon.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] In the 1950s, David Canter was treated by an osteopath who introduced him to the idea of healthy eating.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] While he was converting premises in Carnaby Street for the Craft Potters Association (of which he was a co-founder), a vacant bakery came on to the market nearby and Canter decided to make it into a healthy food salad bar.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] At that time Carnaby Street was, in Canter's words "not swinging, but a street of small shops and cafés." Canter, his wife Kay, and Swann borrowed £500 to start the restaurant.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] The style of decor was also new, although owing something to 1950s coffee bars.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] There were solid natural-coloured oak tables, hand thrown stoneware pottery made by ceramicists Ray Finch and Sidney Tustin at Winchcombe Pottery, heather-brown quarry tiles, woven basket lampshades, and hand-woven seat covers.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] Cranks moved to larger premises in Marshall Street in 1967.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] In the next decade they opened branches at Dartmouth, Totnes, Guildford, Dartington, Heals furniture store in Tottenham Court Road, and the Peter Robinson department store in Oxford Street.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] A sole franchise, the Cranks Grønne Buffet, was opened in Copenhagen.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] Celebrity chef Denis Cotter worked at Cranks in the 1980s.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] In 1987 Kay Canter and Daphne Swann sold Cranks to Guinness.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] Opening more branches under a new business plan, the business encountered financial difficulties, attributed by some to a dated image.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] It was then bought and sold several times, and in the 1990s was rebranded, bringing it in line with contemporary sandwich bars.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] In 1998 it was bought by Capricorn International, who invested £1.5m in the London branches, but continuing losses forced them to close the restaurants.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] The brand was then sold to Nando's Grocery Ltd.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] Most of the Cranks restaurants closed in 2012 and an estimated 60 staff were made redundant.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] Kay Canter died in April 2007 at age 85.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] Daphne Swann died on 28 February 2020 at age 95.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] The current owners have now agreed a sandwich distribution deal with Holland and Barrett in selected stores in London, and a frozen ready meal deal with Waitrose.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] Cranks has been seen as a major factor in the spread of vegetarianism in recent decades.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] It attracted many celebrities who dined there, including Princess Diana, Sir Paul McCartney, Linda McCartney, and Sir Cliff Richard.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] Satirists and cultural critics called vegetarians "cranks" during the twentieth century but "In the 1960s, a vegetarian restaurant took the sting out of over a century of mockery by proudly adopting the name "Cranks"" reported the *Cabinet Magazine*.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] The restaurant became successful quickly, indicating unmet demand for its original menus.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] The Cranks menu at first consisted mainly of salads.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] David Canter wrote that, "In contrast to the traditional tired lettuce that makes the appetite wilt too, these salads could change the eater's whole view of vegetables.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] The vivid combinations of ingredients and colours, crisp from cutting and dressing, were teamed with equally fresh wholemeal rolls, savouries and puddings." Bean soups were another staple.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] Its carrot soup recipe is still used by some who ate at the restaurant.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] Other dishes were added, such as the popular nut roast, homity pie, veg crumble, and carrot cake.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] The Cranks cheese baps were named Best Sandwich in London by the *Evening Standard.* By 1998, the top selling menu items were cous cous with roasted Mediterranean vegetables and stir-fried vegetables with noodles.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] The best-known Cranks dish was the nut roast.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] The *Financial Times* reported in 2021 "In the Cranks cookery book, nut roast is offered up as the veggie gateway drug." The recipe ingredients are one onion, butter or margarine, nuts, wholemeal bread, vegetable stock or water, yeast extract, mixed herbs, salt and pepper.
[src:cranks-restaurant/cranks-restaurant] The Cranks nut roast inspired nut roasts eaten in the United States.
